{{for|the music instrument used in some Chinese opera genres|Sheng (instrument)}}
[[File:Beijing-Opera2.jpg|thumb|Example of a ''Wusheng'' (martial gentleman) character.]]
The '''''Sheng''''' ({{zh|c=生|p=Shēng|l=scholar}}) is the main male role in [[Chinese opera]]. This role has numerous subtypes. The {{transl|zh|''laosheng''}} is a dignified older role. These characters have a gentle and cultivated disposition and wear sensible costumes. One type of {{transl|zh|''laosheng''}} role is the {{transl|zh|''hongsheng''}}, a red-faced older male. The only two {{transl|zh|''hongsheng''}} roles are [[Guan Gong]], the Chinese god of sworn brotherhood, loyalty and righteousness, and [[Emperor Taizu of Song|Zhao Kuang-yin]], the first [[Song Dynasty]] emperor. Young male characters are known as {{transl|zh|''xiaosheng''}}. These characters sing in a high, shrill voice with occasional breaks to represent the voice changing period of adolescence. Depending on the character's rank in society, the costume of the ''xiaosheng'' may be either elaborate or simple.<ref name="tyfo">{{Cite web|url=http://china.tyfo.com/int/ent/opera/peking/peking-index.htm|title=Peking Opera|year=2000|publisher=It's China Network - TYFO.COM|author=Unknown Author|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607182457/http://china.tyfo.com/int/ent/opera/peking/peking-index.htm|archivedate=June 7, 2007}}</ref> On-stage, {{transl|zh|''xiaosheng''}} actors are often involved with beautiful women by virtue of the handsome and young image they project.<ref name="Afternoon Tea">{{cite book | title=Afternoon Tea at the Beijing Opera| url=https://books.google.com/?id=EO7LgHBYmHcC&dq=%22Beijing+opera%22+AND+%22repertoire%22| last=Chengbei| first=Xu| year=2006| pages=163| publisher=Long River Press | isbn=978-1-59265-057-6}}</ref> The {{transl|zh|''wusheng''}} is a martial character for roles involving combat. They are highly trained in acrobatics, and have a natural voice when singing.<ref name="tyfo" /> Troupes will always have a {{transl|zh|''laosheng''}} actor. A {{transl|zh|''xiaosheng''}} actor may also be added to play roles fitting to his age. In addition to these main {{transl|zh|Sheng}}, the troupe will also have a secondary {{transl|zh|''laosheng''}}.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wichmann|first=Elizabeth|title=Listening to Theatre: The Aural Dimension of Beijing Opera|publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]]|page=7–8}}</ref>

